● Yes, it requires a Google account login — Search Console is a Google property.

  Use your personal one. Here's why:

  - Search Console is purely a webmaster tool — it only gives you data about your own site, it's not visible to
  anyone else
  - Setting up a separate account adds friction with no benefit: you'd need to log in and out, manage two accounts,
   and Google actually prefers the site owner to use their main account (it builds trust signals)
  - AdSense (#6) will also need a Google account — having both linked to the same one keeps everything in one place

  The only reason to use a separate account would be if you were handing site management to someone else entirely,
  which isn't the case here.

  So: your personal Google account, and you're good to go.

  Want me to walk you through the steps now?


❯ Yes please: Step #5

● Here's the full walkthrough. It takes about 5 minutes.

  ---
  Step 1 — Open Search Console

  Go to: https://search.google.com/search-console

  Sign in with your personal Google account.

  ---
  Step 2 — Add your property

  Click "Add property" (top-left dropdown).

  Choose "URL prefix" (not Domain) and enter:
  https://claudebeat.ai
  Click Continue.

  ---
  Step 3 — Verify ownership

  Google needs to confirm you own the site. The easiest method for a static site is the HTML file method:

  1. Google will offer you a small file to download, e.g. googleXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX.html
  2. Drop that file into the root of the project (same folder as index.html)
  3. Commit and push it:
  git add googleXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX.html
  git commit -m "Add Google Search Console verification file"
  git push
  4. Wait ~30 seconds for it to go live, then click Verify in Search Console

  ---
  Step 4 — Submit the sitemap

  Once verified, in the left sidebar click Sitemaps, then:

  1. In the "Add a new sitemap" box, enter:
  sitemap.xml
  2. Click Submit

  Google will show it as "Pending" at first — that's normal. It usually processes within a few hours and you'll see
   it change to "Success" with a URL count.

  ---
  Step 5 — Done

  That's it. Google now has a direct invitation to crawl all 112 pages. You'll start seeing data appear in Search
  Console within a few days — impressions first, then clicks as pages begin ranking.

