● Really thoughtful question — and it gets to the heart of the editorial relationship. Let me lay out the realistic
   options:

  ---
  Option A — GitHub Pull Request (my recommendation)

  The cron job writes the day's content to a draft branch and opens a PR automatically. You get a GitHub
  notification, review the actual diff (title, entries, sources used), and click Merge to publish. The VM then
  auto-pulls on merge.

  Pros: You see exactly what's going live. Full audit trail. Works from your phone via the GitHub mobile app. No
  extra infrastructure.
  Cons: Requires you to have the GitHub app or check email notifications.

  ---
  Option B — Email digest before publishing

  The cron job writes the content, then emails you a summary (headlines + sources used) and waits. If you take no
  action within, say, 4 hours, it publishes automatically. A "reject" reply triggers a rollback.

  Pros: Very simple. Works with any email client.
  Cons: The "silent approval" window means content could go live while you're busy. Rollback is messier than a PR.

  ---
  Option C — Telegram bot

  The cron job sends a message to a private Telegram bot with a summary and Approve / Reject buttons. You tap
  Approve from your phone, it publishes.

  Pros: Fastest to act on. Phone-native. Very clean UX.
  Cons: Requires setting up a Telegram bot (~30 min one-off work).

  ---
  My take

  Option A fits most naturally with what you already have — you're already comfortable with GitHub, there's no new
  infrastructure, and reviewing a PR diff is genuinely the best way to see what's about to go live. The GitHub
  mobile app makes it phone-friendly too.

  Option C (Telegram) would be the slickest daily experience if you want a one-tap approval from your phone without
   opening a browser.

  Which direction appeals to you?



